21. opima praeda: a fat prizei —quod si: introducing a conclu- sion. Cf. C. 1, 1, 35. Notice that Horace here makes no mention of Mevius by name, and euphemistic- ally avoids ill-omened expressions such as tuum corpus, which is implied, however. in porrecta. In this way he makes his wish for Mevius' harm all the harsher. Porphyrio saw a special point in Opima, for he remarks apparet et pinguem fnisse (ilsevium).

22. mergos : the voracious coots are, however, not given to eating carrion.
